tion, this book explores what Latinos experience in moving to Richmond and what they bring to a city previously marked by only a black/white ethnic divide. The intersections of geographic mobility, isolation, and segmented assimilation processes are discussed and shown to intensify class differences, as well-educated Latino professionals dominate the cultural and political landscape while less-well-off immigrants remain marginal.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Jun 2024) 0aCommunity lifezVirginiazRichmond. 0aHispanic AmericansxCultural assimilationzVirginiazRichmond. 0aHispanic AmericanszVirginiazRichmondxSocial conditions. 0aSocial classeszVirginiazRichmond. 4aArea Studies : Hispanic Studies. 4aCultural Studies : Cultural Studies. 4aPublic Policy : Immigration. 4aSociology : Ethnicity. 4aSociology : Sociology. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Emigration & Immigration.2bisacsh1 aCavalcanti, H. B., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertSUNY Press eBook Package  Backlist 2000-2013z978311148737340uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978143842881940uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781438428819423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781438428819/original  a978-3-11-148737-3  SUNY Press eBook Package  Backlist 2000-2013c2000d2013  aGBV-deGruyter-alles